ne, rock’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure, enclosed park’. Standish (Gloucestershire) does not appear to have contributed towards the surname.","History: Myles Standish (<i>c.</i> 1584–1656) was a soldier of fortune, from 1620 captain of the <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony. Little is known of his origins and early life, but in his will he claimed to be descended from a leading Catholic family, the Standishes of Standish, Lancashire, England. He also claimed to have been deprived of his inheritance, a claim not confirmed."],"variants":[{"name":"Standage","meanings":["English:","probably a variant of   Standish  .","in Leicestershire and Buckinghamshire, the name may alternatively be from Stanedge Grange in Hartington Nether Quarter or Stanage End in Outseats (both Derbyshire); but evidence is needed for this. The placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, escarpment’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph de Standish was born about 1359, in Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Ralph de Standish. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1359–":"umbes 1359–Surnud","1359–Male":"1359–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1318–1384":"1318–1384","1359":"1359","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1318":"1318","Standish, Wigan, Lan